<paragraph blockId="7.[811,1457,1493,1623]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName authority="Scherber. &amp; Duruiss." authorityName="Scherber. &amp; Duruiss." authorityYear="2019" box="[813,1210,1493,1517]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="harimalalae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[813,1001,1493,1517]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Begonia harimalalae</emphasis>
Scherber. &amp; Duruiss.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1217,1292,1493,1516]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be compared to 
<taxonomicName box="[840,945,1520,1543]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erminea">
<emphasis box="[840,945,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">B. erminea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it differs by the much thicker, more numerous (3-8 vs 2-5) and larger (10-15 vs 
<quantity box="[1124,1193,1546,1570]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" unit="cm" value="6.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="4.0">4-8 cm</quantity>
) leaves, which are glabrous, without spiculiform hairs adaxially and with the margins shallowly and sparsely serrate vs densely biserrate.
</paragraph>
